# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

Successfully implemented Vercel Speed Insights for the Next.js application.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` package using npm
- Updated `package.json` with new dependency
- Generated updated `package-lock.json` to lock dependency versions

### 2. Integration with App Router
Modified `src/app/layout.js`:
- Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/next';`
- Placed `<SpeedInsights />` component inside the `<body>` tag after `{children}`
- This follows Next.js 13.5+ App Router best practices

## Implementation Details

Since this project uses:
- Next.js 14.2.35 (supports App Router)
- JavaScript (not TypeScript)
- App Router structure (`src/app/layout.js`)

The implementation used the recommended approach for App Router:
- Imported from `@vercel/speed-insights/next` (automatic route tracking)
- Added component to root layout for application-wide coverage
- No manual route configuration needed (automatic in Next.js 13.5+)

## Verification

✅ Build completed successfully (`npm run build`)
✅ No linting errors introduced
✅ All dependencies properly installed and locked
✅ SpeedInsights component properly integrated into root layout

## Files Modified

1. `package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
2. `package-lock.json` - Updated with new dependency tree
3. `src/app/layout.js` - Added SpeedInsights component import and usage

The Speed Insights component will now automatically track page views and web vitals metrics when the application is deployed to Vercel.
